ce:section.ce:para:
Briefly, the contributions of adsorption, free radical pathway, and nonradical pathway are different in various persulfate-based catalytic systems, especially for different carbon materials (Table 1
                           ). The surface active sites of carbon materials could result in the changes of the degradation pathways and removal rates [13]. Moreover, the carbon matrix with ketonic groups and sp2 hybridized orbitals could serve as electron transfer tunnels from antibiotic pollutants to persulfate for the generation of SO4
                           •− and HO•. Both the intrinsic defects and foreign defects of carbon materials could produce redistribution of regional electrons and changes of electric density. Therefore, the defects of carbon materials could serve as active sites to promote both the nonradical pathway and radical pathway. In the free radical pathway, the redox potential of free radicals and degradation rate are high. Besides, the by-products of degradation process can be completely oxidized into CO2 and H2O, which is impossible in the nonradical pathway. Nevertheless, the nonradical pathway is more selective, and the removal process can be controlled in a much gentler and easier way [28,40,47].
